# OpenShift Virtualization Cookbook - Project Rules

## Branch Management and Version Control

Git policy (local branches only, no push, no PRs, commit attribution) is enforced by `shared-constraints.mdc`. Additional project-level guidance:

- For each task, create a new branch with a descriptive name
- Use clear, descriptive commit messages that explain what was changed and why
- Keep commits focused on a single logical change

## Communication and Documentation Style

- NEVER use icons or emojis in any documentation, code comments, or communication
- Use clear, professional technical writing
- Keep language concise and to the point
- Use AsciiDoc formatting appropriately (code blocks, headers, lists, tables, callouts)
- Follow Antora documentation best practices

## Verification and Research Requirements

- ALWAYS verify information against official OpenShift documentation before implementation
- Check OKD, KubeVirt, and related project documentation for accuracy
- Search online documentation for current best practices and latest features
- Verify API versions and resource definitions are current for the target OpenShift version
- Cross-reference multiple sources when uncertain

## Documentation Content Requirements

### Length and Scope
- Keep documentation pages to appropriate read time for the topic
- Focus on one specific topic or use case per page
- Avoid unnecessary complexity or tangential topics
- Use clear, step-by-step instructions

### Structure
- Start with a brief overview of what will be accomplished
- List prerequisites clearly
- Provide complete YAML manifests and code examples, not partial snippets
- Include verification steps after each major section
- End with a summary of what was accomplished
- Add "See Also" sections linking to related content

### Technical Accuracy
- Use correct terminology (e.g., "logical network interface name" not "physnet name")
- Specify exact resource names, namespaces, and versions
- Include all required fields in YAML manifests
- Explain non-obvious configuration choices
- Link to official documentation where appropriate

## File Organization

### Module Structure
- Place content in appropriate modules under `modules/`
- Each module should have:
  - `pages/` directory for AsciiDoc content files
  - `nav.adoc` for navigation structure
  - `images/` directory if module needs images (optional)
- Use descriptive, kebab-case filenames for pages
- Keep related content together in the same module

### AsciiDoc Files
- Start each page with a level-1 heading (`= Page Title`)
- Use consistent header hierarchy (`=`, `==`, `===`)
- Add blank lines between sections for readability
- Use appropriate AsciiDoc attributes when needed

### Navigation Files
- Keep `nav.adoc` files updated when adding/removing pages
- When adding a new page to a module, also update the module's `index.adoc` Sections list (if one exists) to include a corresponding xref entry
- Use logical hierarchy in navigation
- Use clear, descriptive navigation labels
- Test navigation in preview after changes

## Code and Manifest Quality

- Use proper YAML indentation (2 spaces)
- Include all required Kubernetes/OpenShift metadata (apiVersion, kind, metadata, spec)
- Add comments in YAML where configuration choices are non-obvious
- Use descriptive resource names
- Follow OpenShift and Kubernetes naming conventions
- Validate YAML syntax before committing
- Use proper AsciiDoc code block syntax with language specification:
  ```
  [source,yaml]
  ----
  yaml content
  ----
  ```

## AsciiDoc Best Practices

### Code Blocks
- Always specify language: `[source,bash]`, `[source,yaml]`, `[source,json]`
- Use `role=execute` for commands users should run: `[source,bash,role=execute]`
- When a code block starts with a shell command that embeds YAML (e.g., `oc apply -f - <<EOF`), tag it `[source,bash,role=execute]`, not `[source,yaml]`. Reserve `[source,yaml]` for standalone YAML content that is not wrapped in a shell command.
- Each code block should contain a single command (or a single tightly coupled pipeline). When a step involves multiple commands, use a separate code block for each with a brief sentence of prose in between.
- Do not mix host-side commands (`oc`, `virtctl`, `kubectl`) and guest-side commands (commands run inside a VM) in the same code block. Separate them with prose explaining the context switch.
- Preserve proper indentation
- Test that code blocks render correctly in preview

### Cross-References
- Use `xref:` for internal links within the documentation
- Same module: `xref:page-name.adoc[Link Text]`
- Different module: `xref:module-name:page-name.adoc[Link Text]`
- External links: `https://example.com[Link Text,window=_blank]`
- Verify all xrefs resolve correctly by building the site

### Images
- Place images in module's `images/` directory
- Reference with: `image::filename.png[Alt Text]`
- Use descriptive alt text for accessibility
- Verify images display in preview

### Callouts
- Use AsciiDoc admonitions appropriately:
  - `NOTE:` for informational notes
  - `WARNING:` for important warnings
  - `IMPORTANT:` for critical information
  - `TIP:` for helpful tips
  - `CAUTION:` for caution messages

### Tables
- Use proper AsciiDoc table syntax with column definitions
- Include header rows when appropriate
- Test table rendering in preview

