## Cloud-init and VM Configuration

- Use networkData section for network configuration in cloud-init
- Use the `write_files` cloud-init module instead of shell file-creation commands (`echo`, `cat > file <<HEREDOC`, `tee`, etc.) in `runcmd`. The `write_files` module is declarative, avoids shell quoting issues, and is easier to read in YAML.
- Match interface names to KubeVirt's predictable naming (enpXsY format)
- Explicitly disable DHCP when using static IPs (dhcp4: false, dhcp6: false)
- Document verification steps for cloud-init configurations

## Network Configuration Best Practices

- Explain bridge mapping clearly (physical bridge to logical network name)
- Specify VLAN tagging requirements (trunk mode on physical switches)
- Clarify IPAM behavior (when OVN-Kubernetes provides IPs vs external DHCP vs cloud-init)
- Include physicalNetworkName in NADs for localnet topologies
- Document bridge verification steps using ovs-vsctl commands

## Storage Configuration Best Practices

- Always specify a default deviceClass when documenting LVMCluster
- Explain the importance of default StorageClass for OpenShift Virtualization
- Document storage verification commands
- Include PVC testing examples in storage documentation

## Error Handling

- When build errors occur, troubleshoot systematically
- Check Antora error messages for specific issues
- Common issues:
  - Broken xref links
  - Invalid AsciiDoc syntax
  - Missing files in navigation
  - Incorrect image paths
- Fix issues and verify with another build

## Git and GitHub Workflow

Core git policy and commit attribution are in `shared-constraints.mdc`. Additional workflow guidance:

- Stage only relevant files for each commit
- Review changes before committing (`git diff`)
- Use git status to verify clean working tree
- Handle merge conflicts carefully, preserving both old and new work appropriately

## Resource Naming Conventions

- Use descriptive names for Kubernetes resources
- Include purpose or topology in network resource names (e.g., localnet-vlan-100)
- Use consistent namespace naming
- Follow existing naming patterns in examples

## Cross-Module Consistency

- Use similar structure across all modules
- Maintain consistent terminology throughout
- Reference related content where appropriate using xrefs
- Build on concepts from other modules without excessive repetition

